  "eprint": {
    "title": "LadderLeak: Breaking ECDSA With Less Than One Bit Of Nonce Leakage",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Diego F.  Aranha",
        "email": "dfaranha@eng",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Felipe Rodrigues Novaes",
        "email": "dkra135663@students",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Akira Takahashi",
        "email": "brtakahashi@cs",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Mehdi Tibouchi",
        "email": "58s@kyoto-u",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Yuval Yarom",
        "email": "br@hco",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Although it is one of the most popular signature schemes today, ECDSA\npresents a number of implementation pitfalls, in particular due to the\nvery sensitive nature of the random value (known as the nonce)\ngenerated as part of the signing algorithm. It is known that any small\namount of nonce exposure or nonce bias can in principle lead to a full\nkey recovery: the key recovery is then a particular instance of Boneh and\nVenkatesan's hidden number problem (HNP). That observation has\nbeen practically exploited in many attacks in the literature, taking\nadvantage of implementation defects or side-channel vulnerabilities in\nvarious concrete ECDSA implementations. However, most of the attacks so\nfar have relied on at least 2 bits of nonce bias (except for the\nspecial case of curves at the $80$-bit security level, for which attacks\nagainst $1$-bit biases are known, albeit with a very high number of\nrequired signatures).\n\nIn this paper, we uncover LadderLeak, a novel class of\nside-channel vulnerabilities in implementations of the Montgomery ladder\nused in ECDSA scalar multiplication. The vulnerability is in particular\npresent in several recent versions of OpenSSL. However, it leaks\nless than $1$ bit of information about the nonce, in the sense\nthat it reveals the most significant bit of the nonce, but with\nprobability $<1$. Exploiting such a mild leakage would be intractable\nusing techniques present in the literature so far. However, we present a\nnumber of theoretical improvements of the Fourier analysis approach to\nsolving the HNP (an approach originally due to Bleichenbacher), and this\nlets us practically break LadderLeak-vulnerable ECDSA\nimplementations instantiated over the sect163r1 and NIST P-192\nelliptic curves. In so doing, we achieve several significant\ncomputational records in practical attacks against the HNP.",
    "keywords": [
      "side-channel attack",
      "cache attack",
      "ECDSA",
      "OpenSSL",
      "Montgomery Ladder",
      "hidden number problem",
      "Bleichenbacher's attack",
      "generalized birthday problem"
    ],
